# Rule: never name third-party reference projects in FERAL-AI deliverables

## What

When you adopt a pattern, idea, or architecture from a third-party project, **do not name that project** in any shipped artifact. The project belongs to FERAL-AI; references to the source-of-inspiration belong in private analysis documents only.

## Forbidden in shipped artifacts (NEVER name a third-party project here)

- `SECURITY.md`, `README.md`, `CONTRIBUTING.md`, `LICENSE` — repo-root user-facing docs
- `docs/mintlify/**` — published documentation
- Any `*.md` outside `docs/AGENT_PROMPTS*.md` and `docs/OPENCLAW_LESSONS*.md`
- Source code: `feral-core/**/*.py`, `feral-client*/**/*.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}`, `feral-nodes/**`, `desktop/**`, `feral-extension/**`, `feral-ha-addon/**`, `feral-channels/**`, `sdk/**`, `templates/**`, `apps/**`
- Test files: `feral-core/tests/**/*.py`, `feral-client*/src/__tests__/**`
- Inline code comments and docstrings inside the above paths
- PR titles, PR bodies, commit messages, tag annotations
- Workflow files under `.github/workflows/**`
- Schema files (`*.json`, `*.yaml`) under `feral-core/`, `feral-channels/`, `ops/`

## Exempt locations (third-party names are OK here)

- `docs/OPENCLAW_LESSONS.md` — internal comparative architecture analysis
- `docs/OPENCLAW_LESSONS_PROMPT.md` — the prompt that produced the analysis
- `docs/AGENT_PROMPTS.md` — internal conductor prompt library (per-workstream prompts may cite the reference architecture inside the prompt body, since the prompt itself is internal)
- `docs/AGENT_PROMPTS_FOLLOWUPS.md` — internal conductor follow-up log
- `docs/critique.md` — internal architecture critique
- `CHANGELOG.md` historical entries dated on or before 2026-04-25 — left untouched for honest historical record; new entries from 2026-04-26 onward MUST follow this rule

## Replacement vocabulary (what to write instead)

| Instead of | Write |
|---|---|
| "openclaw does X" / "modeled on openclaw's Y" | "the reference architecture", "the comparative study (see `docs/OPENCLAW_LESSONS.md`)", or just describe what FERAL does without comparison |
| "ported from openclaw's `path/file.ts`" | "based on the pattern documented in `docs/OPENCLAW_LESSONS.md` §N" |
| "openclaw's getShellConfig() resolves to" | (delete the comparison entirely; explain what FERAL does on its own terms) |
| "follows openclaw's session-spawn allowlist test names" | "the canonical lifecycle test set: allowlist / cron-note / lifecycle / model / scope" |
| Test method named `test_matches_openclaw_behaviour` | `test_<the actual contract being verified>` (name the contract, not the source) |

## Rationale

This is FERAL-AI's product. We learn from many places, but every line we ship is **ours** and stands on its own merit. Citing the source-of-inspiration in a published artifact:

1. Implies we're a derivative work when we're not — every workstream rewrote the pattern in our own architecture, language, and threat model.
2. Confuses users — they don't know what openclaw is, and they shouldn't have to.
3. Disrespects FERAL's identity — `SECURITY.md` is our security posture, not a comparative essay.
4. Creates downstream surprise — every commit message, file comment, and test name becomes a discoverable advert for someone else's project on our GitHub.

## Enforcement

- **Pre-commit / CI gate (future):** a small linter that fails on the literal string `openclaw` (case-insensitive) in any path NOT listed under "Exempt locations". Filed as a follow-up under W31.
- **Subagent prompts must include:** "Do not name openclaw or any third-party reference project in the artifact you are about to write. If you adopted a pattern from one, describe what FERAL does in our own terms; the comparative study lives in `docs/OPENCLAW_LESSONS.md` and is the only place that names sources."
- **Conductor sweep:** after every wave, grep deliverables for forbidden mentions and either rewrite the prose or open a small `chore: scrub third-party project names` PR.

## Process for future "openclaw-inspired" work

1. The internal `docs/OPENCLAW_LESSONS.md` analysis cites the source-of-truth path:line for every adopted pattern. Keep doing that.
2. The workstream prompt (in `docs/AGENT_PROMPTS.md`) may reference the analysis doc by section, e.g. "see `docs/OPENCLAW_LESSONS.md` §10 W##". That's fine.
3. The PR body, commit message, code comments, docs, and tests must describe what FERAL does **on its own terms** — no "ported from X", "openclaw-style Y", "matches openclaw's Z".
4. If a test is verifying a specific contract that came out of the analysis, name the test for the **contract** (e.g. `test_per_parent_allowlist_default_deny`), not the source (`test_matches_openclaw_behaviour`).
